Did the Duck (curve) land in California?

EIA Open Data

library(EIAdata)
data_category <- "EBA.CISO-ALL.D.H"

#Hourly Electricity Demand Data for 
#California Independent Systems Operator
#CAISO serves electricity to 80% of CA (and a tiny chunk of Nevada)
#https://www.eia.gov/opendata

df <- EIAdata::getEIA(data_category,API_key)
head(df)
##                  Date Demand
## 1 2015-07-01 01:00:00  31486
## 2 2015-07-01 02:00:00  28989
## 3 2015-07-01 03:00:00  27416
## 4 2015-07-01 04:00:00  26388
## 5 2015-07-01 05:00:00  25661
## 6 2015-07-01 06:00:00  25845

Timezones!

The dataset is provided in UTC(+0). The data represents electrical demand in California, which is UTC(-8).

Sys.setenv(TZ="America/Los_Angeles")

What does a day look like?

d2016_03_31 <- dplyr::filter(df,Date >= "2016-03-31" &
                               Date < "2016-04-01")
plot(d2016_03_31, type = "l", xlab="Hour - March 31st 2016")

## Enter GGPLOT2!

library(ggplot2)

Boring chart - let’s spice it up

ggplot(d2016_03_31) +
    geom_line(aes(x=Date, y = Demand), color = "blue")

Mutate to extract year, month, day, and hour

df <- dplyr::mutate(df,Year = year(Date),
                    Month = month(Date),
                    Day = day(Date),
                    Hour = hour(Date))
head(df)
##                  Date Demand Year Month Day Hour
## 1 2015-07-01 01:00:00  31486 2015     7   1    1
## 2 2015-07-01 02:00:00  28989 2015     7   1    2
## 3 2015-07-01 03:00:00  27416 2015     7   1    3
## 4 2015-07-01 04:00:00  26388 2015     7   1    4
## 5 2015-07-01 05:00:00  25661 2015     7   1    5
## 6 2015-07-01 06:00:00  25845 2015     7   1    6

Filtering and Plotting multiple years

m3_d31 <- dplyr::filter(df,Month ==3 & Day ==31)
ggplot(m3_d31) +
    geom_line(aes(x=Hour, y = Demand, group = Year, color = factor(Year)))+
    scale_color_discrete(name = "Year")+
    scale_y_continuous(name= "Demand - MW")

Plotting multiple years

What about New Year’s Day?

m1_d1 <- dplyr::filter(df,Month ==1 & Day ==1)

Takeaways

  • Renewable energy has gotten incredibly cheap.
  • Grid operators need to adapt to these changes
  • GGPlot2 is more powerful and beautiful than base R
  • Adding annotations and flourishes makes data visualization more interesting.
